Usage:
  tail [flags]

Flags:
  -c, --command string     the address of the executable file to be tracked. As an alternative, the pipe can be used to start
  -f, --full               full output
  -h, --help               display help information
  -i, --icon string        icon in the program title
  -r, --indicator string   specifying an element to display the program's running process (none, roller, bolded-roller, pipe) (default "none")
  -l, --length int         maximum length of the output line
  -n, --lines int          maximum number of lines for output to the screen (default 5)
  -o, --output string      text output process option (modes: direct - output on new data, thread - periodic redraw) (default "direct")
  -s, --size uint          maximum size of the stored buffer in number of lines (default 10240)
  -t, --template string    data output template (none, minimal, full) (default "none")
  -a, --title string       name in the program title
  -v, --version            display version information
Tail
 Program for monitoring command execution and displaying their output in real-time with various modes and display templates. Supports both direct command execution and data retrieval via pipe. Deletes log upon successful completion, ensuring cleanliness and relevance of displayed information.
For changing the language, when starting, specify the LANG variable in the format ru_RU.UTF-8, or en_US.UTF-8 (the first two characters are important)
Examples of use:
  tail -n 10 -o thread -t minimal -- ping google.com
  tail -s 1000 -o direct -t full -- ping google.com
  echo 'Hello World' | tail -o direct -t none
